---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const jsonExample = `{
  "name": "Alice",
  "age": 30,
  "skills": ["JavaScript", "Python", "SQL"],
  "active": true
}`;

const jsonMinified = `{"users":[{"id":1,"name":"Alice","email":"alice@example.com","roles":["admin","editor"]},{"id":2,"name":"Bob","email":"bob@example.com","roles":["viewer"]}]}`;

const jsonFormatted = `{
  "users": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "Alice",
      "email": "alice@example.com",
      "roles": ["admin", "editor"]
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "name": "Bob",
      "email": "bob@example.com",
      "roles": ["viewer"]
    }
  ]
}`;

const trailingComma = `{ "name": "Alice", "age": 30, }  // Error: trailing comma`;
const singleQuotes = `{ 'name': 'Alice' }  // Error: single quotes`;
const unquotedKey = `{ name: "Alice" }  // Error: unquoted key`;
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Format JSON: A Complete Guide for Developers"
  description="Learn how to format, beautify, and validate JSON data. Understand what JSON is, why formatting matters, common errors, and best practices for developers."
  date="2026-04-02"
  readingTime="5"
>
  <p>If you work with APIs, configuration files, or web development in any capacity, you have almost certainly encountered JSON. It is the universal data format of the modern web, but raw JSON can be incredibly difficult to read without proper formatting. In this guide, you will learn what JSON is, why formatting it properly matters, how to spot common errors, and the best practices every developer should follow.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">What Is JSON?</h2>
  <p>JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight, text-based data interchange format. Despite its name, JSON is language-independent and used across virtually every programming language including Python, Java, Go, Ruby, PHP, and of course JavaScript and TypeScript.</p>
  <p class="mt-3">A typical JSON structure looks like this:</p>
  <pre class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{jsonExample}</code></pre>
  <p class="mt-3">JSON supports six data types: strings, numbers, booleans, null, arrays, and objects. Its simplicity is what makes it so widely adopted. Unlike XML, JSON has minimal syntax overhead, making it both human-readable and efficient for machines to parse.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Why Does JSON Formatting Matter?</h2>
  <p>API responses, database exports, and configuration files often contain JSON in a single, compressed line called minified JSON. While this is efficient for data transfer, it is nearly impossible for humans to read and debug. Consider this minified response:</p>
  <pre class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{jsonMinified}</code></pre>
  <p class="mt-3">Now compare it with the formatted version:</p>
  <pre class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{jsonFormatted}</code></pre>
  <p class="mt-3">The formatted version is immediately understandable. Proper formatting helps you identify the data structure at a glance, spot missing fields, debug API issues faster, and share data with teammates in a readable way.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">How to Format JSON Using Our Free Tool</h2>
