  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Common JSON Errors and How to Fix Them</h2>
  <p>Even experienced developers run into JSON syntax errors. Here are the most common issues:</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Trailing Commas</h3>
  <p>JSON does not allow trailing commas after the last item in an array or object. This is valid in JavaScript but will break JSON parsing:</p>
  <pre class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{trailingComma}</code></pre>
  <p class="mt-2">Remove the comma after the last property to fix it.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Single Quotes Instead of Double Quotes</h3>
  <p>JSON requires double quotes for strings. Single quotes are not valid:</p>
  <pre class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{singleQuotes}</code></pre>
  <p class="mt-2">Always use double quotes: <code set:html={'{ "name": "Alice" }'} /></p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Unquoted Keys</h3>
  <p>All keys in JSON must be wrapped in double quotes. Unquoted keys work in JavaScript objects but not in JSON:</p>
  <pre class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-3 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>{unquotedKey}</code></pre>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Comments in JSON</h3>
  <p>Standard JSON does not support comments. If you need comments in configuration files, consider using JSONC (JSON with Comments) or YAML instead. Some tools like VS Code support JSONC natively for settings files.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Missing or Extra Brackets</h3>
  <p>Mismatched curly braces or square brackets are easy to miss in large JSON files. A formatter tool will highlight exactly where the mismatch occurs, saving you significant debugging time.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">JSON Best Practices for Developers</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Use consistent indentation</strong> &mdash; Two spaces is the most common convention for JSON files. Four spaces is also acceptable. Be consistent across your project.</li>
    <li><strong>Use camelCase for keys</strong> &mdash; While not required, camelCase (e.g., <code>firstName</code>) is the most common convention in JSON, especially in JavaScript ecosystems.</li>
    <li><strong>Validate before deploying</strong> &mdash; Always validate your JSON configuration files before deploying. A single misplaced comma can bring down an entire application.</li>
    <li><strong>Minify for production</strong> &mdash; When sending JSON over the network, use minified JSON to reduce payload size. This can significantly improve API response times.</li>
    <li><strong>Use a schema</strong> &mdash; For complex JSON structures, define a JSON Schema to validate data shape and types. This catches errors early and serves as documentation.</li>
    <li><strong>Handle encoding properly</strong> &mdash; JSON uses UTF-8 encoding. Make sure special characters and unicode are properly escaped when generating JSON programmatically.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">JSON Formatting in Your Editor</h2>
  <p>Most code editors offer built-in or extension-based JSON formatting. In VS Code, you can format a JSON file by pressing <code>Shift+Alt+F</code> (Windows) or <code>Shift+Option+F</code> (Mac). For quick one-off formatting tasks, however, an online tool is often faster since you can paste, format, and copy without opening a file.</p>
  <p class="mt-3">Command-line tools like <code>jq</code> and <code>python -m json.tool</code> are also excellent for formatting JSON in terminal workflows and shell scripts.</p>

